hands_on_practices.solution:
We model the radiative transfer of a background emission line from the hot core through a cooler absorbing atmosphere using the formal solution of the transfer equation along a slab of optical depth $	au_{
u}$:
$$
I_{	ext{obs}}(
u)=I_{	ext{em}}(
u)\exp(-	au_{
u})+\int_{0}^{	au_{
u}} S_{
u}(t)\exp ig(-( 	au_{
u}-t) ig)\,dt.
$$
Assuming the atmosphere is isothermal and homogeneous across the line of sight, the source function $S_{
u}$ is independent of $t$, so the integral evaluates to
$$
I_{	ext{obs}}(
u)=I_{	ext{em}}(
u)\exp(-	au_{
u})+S_{
u} ig(1-\exp(-	au_{
u}) ig).
$$
Because the atmosphere is cooler than the core and “primarily absorbs rather than emits,” its source function satisfies $S_{
u}\ll I_{	ext{em}}(
u)$ near the line, and the line optical depth is sharply frequency dependent. Let the line optical depth be
$$
	au_{
u}=	au_{0}\,\phi(
u),
$$
with a normalized line profile $\phi(
u)$ satisfying $\phi(
u_{0})=1$ and $\phi(
u)$ sharply peaked at $
u_{0}$. The statement that the optical depth is “sufficiently large” implies $	au_{0}\gg 1$.

Evaluate the observed intensity at key frequency regimes.

1) At line center $
u=
u_{0}$:
$$
	au_{
u_{0}}=	au_{0}\gg 1 \quad\Rightarrow\quad \exp(-	au_{
u_{0}})\approx 0,
$$
hence
$$
I_{	ext{obs}}(
u_{0})\approx S_{
u}.
$$
Since $S_{
u}\ll I_{	ext{em}}(
u_{0})$, the intensity at the line center is strongly suppressed relative to the background emission, producing a central minimum.

2) In the line wings, $|
u-
u_{0}|\gg$ line width, so $\phi(
u)\ll 1$ and thus $	au_{
u}\ll 1$. Expanding to first order in $	au_{
u}$,
$$
I_{	ext{obs}}(
u)\approx I_{	ext{em}}(
u) ig(1-	au_{
u} ig)+S_{
u}	au_{
u}
= I_{	ext{em}}(
u)-	au_{
u} ig[I_{	ext{em}}(
u)-S_{
u} ig].
$$
Because $I_{	ext{em}}(
u)>S_{
u}$, the correction is a small reduction from $I_{	ext{em}}(
u)$, so the wings remain close to the original emission intensity.

Combining these limits, the strong absorption at $
u_{0}$ removes the line core while leaving the wings relatively unaffected. As $
u$ moves away from $
u_{0}$, $	au_{
u}$ decreases from $\gg 1$ to $\ll 1$, so $I_{	ext{obs}}(
u)$ transitions from $S_{
u}$ (small) up toward $I_{	ext{em}}(
u)$, producing two local maxima on either side of the central dip. This is the classic self-reversed emission profile caused by resonant absorption in a cooler overlying layer.

Therefore, the observed profile exhibits a central minimum at or very near $
u_{0}$, with two local intensity maxima flanking it. This corresponds to option A. The other options are inconsistent with the frequency-dependent attenuation implied by $	au_{
u}=	au_{0}\phi(
u)$: there is no uniform suppression (contradicting D), no net frequency shift from simple absorption (contradicting C), absorption is strongest at line center not the wings (contradicting E), and a single broadened peak (B) is not produced when the core is strongly suppressed relative to the wings.
